<Docs title="Introduction" description="Capability routing for language models.">
  <p class="eyebrow">smol.router</p>
  <h1>Introduction.</h1>
  <p class="lead"><strong>smol.router</strong> is a small, calibrated classifier that sends each prompt to the cheapest model likely to answer it correctly, then escalates when reality disagrees.</p>
  
  <p>Rather than using large language models to route traffic—which defeats the purpose of cost-saving—smol.router uses a lightweight linear classifier trained directly on your benchmarked data. It runs locally without heavy dependencies, adding less than a millisecond of overhead.</p>

  <h2>Core Principles</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Predict capability:</strong> A hashed-feature linear model estimates the minimum tier (low, medium, high) required by the prompt.</li>
    <li><strong>Price the risk:</strong> A deterministic policy bounds the decision, balancing provider cost against the real damage of under-routing.</li>
    <li><strong>Check the answer:</strong> Validate provider output at the application edge and automatically step up a tier if it fails.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why this approach?</h2>
  <p>Intelligence is expensive. You should use exactly enough for each request. Hand-written prompt lengths or regex matching are fragile, while LLM-based routing is slow and costly.</p>
  <p>By benchmark-testing your actual models to see which tier passes your evaluators, smol.router learns the underlying distribution of your prompt capability requirements.</p>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <div class="feature-grid">
    <article>
      <h3>Zero runtime dependencies</h3>
      <p>The SDK has zero external library dependencies, meaning you can drop it into any Python environment.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Immutable execution</h3>
      <p>Decisions and metrics are fully inspectable, with immutable Results and explicit Error types.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Strict constraints</h3>
      <p>Artifacts are hard-capped at 64MB and strict schema validation prevents tampering or corruption in CI.</p>
    </article>
  </div>

